{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474404"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:20:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:20:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12058"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12058"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.1,0.56,0.11,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4625"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47582"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4625"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12058"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32298"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"123"},{"type":"tags","id":"1186"},{"type":"tags","id":"1244"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7006"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7093"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12280"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38417"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47582"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of worsening pain in his left arm. His arm had been aching for a couple of weeks, which he attributed to a fall from his skateboard. However, two days ago, the pain intensified when he lifted a heavy suitcase. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date. On examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 80/min, blood pressure 120/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Movement of the left arm causes pain, and there is tenderness over the lateral aspect of the upper arm. An X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ewing sarcoma","Osteochondroma","Osteosarcoma","Chondrosarcoma","Osteomyelitis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe radiological findings show a heterogeneous, cystic expanding lesion with medullary and cortical destruction, typical of an \u003Cstrong\u003Eosteosarcoma\u003C/strong\u003E. The humerus is not an uncommon site for an osteosarcoma; approximately 15% of primary tumours arise here. Other common sites include the femur and tibia. Furthermore, the history suggests a pathological fracture occurred when lifting the heavy suitcase. A low-impact fracture like this should raise suspicion of a malignancy until proven otherwise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEwing sarcoma\u003C/strong\u003E is another primary bone malignancy that can occur in this age group. However, it typically presents with a more aggressive clinical course and often shows a \u0027onion-skin\u0027 periosteal reaction on X-ray, which is not seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteochondroma\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common benign bone tumour in children and adolescents. However, it typically appears as a cartilage-capped bony projection on the external surface of bones, which is not consistent with the radiographic findings in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChondrosarcoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a malignant cartilaginous tumour that is rare in this age group, typically affecting older adults. It usually presents as a lytic lesion with a characteristic \u0027ring and arc\u0027 calcification pattern, which is not seen in this X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteomyelitis\u003C/strong\u003E generally presents with pain, swelling, and fevers, which is quite different from the scenario presented above. Radiographic findings generally show signs of osteopenia and bony lysis, often with periosteal reaction, which are not evident in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Osteosarcoma can cause pathological fractures, and should be a top differential for acute onset bone pain in paediatric patients until excluded.","Radiological features of osteosarcoma include heterogeneous, cystic expanding lesions with medullary and cortical destruction."],"references":["Ferguson J, Turner SP. Bone Cancer: Diagnosis and Treatment Principles. Am Fam Physician. 2018; 98:205-13.","American Academy of Family Physicians (AAFP). Acute poststreptococcal glomerulonephritis: diagnosis and treatment. Am Fam Physician. 2018 Aug 15;98(4):205-6. Available from: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2018/0815/p205.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32298"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12058"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17336"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17336","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17336"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/aa539be4-071c-4ce8-8a76-a9d4ed67724f.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/aa539be4-071c-4ce8-8a76-a9d4ed67724f.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":651}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32298","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/32298"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-24T19:47:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-06-24T19:47:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4625"}},"conten